      "question": "Show that for any positive integer $n$, the number $7^n$ can never end with the digit $0$ or $5$.",
      "answer": "The prime factorisation of $7^n$ contains only the prime $7$, which does not include $2$ or $5$.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "For a number to end in $0$, its prime factorisation must contain the factors $2$ and $5$.",
          "For a number to end in $5$, its prime factorisation must contain the factor $5$.",
          "The prime factorisation of $7^n$ is $(7)^n = 7 \\times 7 \\times \\dots \\times 7$ ($n$ times).",
          "Since the only prime factor in $7^n$ is $7$, the number cannot contain $2$ or $5$ as factors, hence it cannot end in $0$ or $5$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$7^n = (7)^n \\implies \\text{Prime factors of } 7^n \\text{ are only } \\{7\\} \\\\ \\text{For a number to end in } 0, \\text{ its prime factors must include } 2 \\times 5 \\\\ \\text{For a number to end in } 5, \\text{ its prime factors must include } 5 \\\\ \\text{Since } 2 \\notin \\{7\\} \\text{ and } 5 \\notin \\{7\\}, 7^n \\text{ cannot end in } 0 \\text{ or } 5$"
      },
