    {
      "question": "A merchant has three types of oil: $403$ litres of mustard oil, $465$ litres of sunflower oil, and $496$ litres of soyabean oil. He wants to pack these into tins of equal capacity such that each tin is filled completely. Find the maximum capacity of such a tin.",
      "answer": "$31$ litres",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "To find the maximum capacity of the tin that can pack each type of oil completely, we must calculate the Highest Common Factor (HCF) of $403$, $465$, and $496$.",
          "Prime factorise the numbers: $403 = 13 \\times 31$, $465 = 3 \\times 5 \\times 31$, and $496 = 2^4 \\times 31$.",
          "The common prime factor present in all three numbers is $31$.",
          "Thus, the HCF is $31$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$403 = 13 \\times 31 \\\\ 465 = 3 \\times 5 \\times 31 \\\\ 496 = 2^4 \\times 31 \\\\ \\text{HCF}(403, 465, 496) = 31"
      },
